You said:
https://www.vectorandbeyond.com/ Can I make it on Shopify and wix
ChatGPT said:

Yes you can build a website like Vector and Beyond on either Shopify or Wix. Heres a breakdown of how each platform can work for you, plus some things to think about (and you pick what you prefer).

What you can do

  • On either platform you can create portfolio-style pages (e.g., Services, About, Contact, Portfolio).

  • You can use visual design, images, branding to make it look like a creative agency site (as Vector and Beyond does).

  • You can integrate contact forms, links to social media or Behance (as their site links to Behance) and basically replicate that structure.

  • Wix is especially friendly for more freestyle site design (drag-and-drop). Shopify can also handle pages like that, though it is more e-commerce-centric.

Platform differences & things to check

With Wix:

  • Easier for purely content/portfolio websites. If your site is more about showing work and less about selling products, Wix is straightforward.

  • Youll have flexibility in layout, animation, creative control.

  • If you later want to sell services/products, Wix also supports that, but its not as commerce-native as Shopify.

  • Since you told me you usually prefer to express thoughts and then decide, if your site is going to evolve (maybe adding bookings, services, brand work) Wix may be very comfortable.

With Shopify:

  • Shopify is built primarily for online stores product listings, checkouts, inventory, payments.

  • If you anticipate turning the site into a service-commerce model (like selling brand-strategy packages, design templates, or other digital goods) Shopify gives you a robust commerce backend.

  • That said, if you just want a portfolio site and dont want to sell, Shopify might be overkill (and a bit more expensive, potentially).

  • If using Shopify for a non-store site youll still pay for the store infrastructure; there may be extra complexity.

My suggestion for you

Since you are a student, youre working through many things (book writing, studies, site preferences) and you said you like to express thoughts first. So:

  • If the goal is: show my work, design services, maybe brand story, no immediate product sales go with Wix. Simple, fast, flexible.

  • If the goal is: show my work + sell digital products/services (e.g., design templates, brand-packages for others, etc) go with Shopify.

  • You could also start with Wix and later pivot to Shopify when your sales side gets stronger.

  • Make sure whichever you pick: pick a good template/theme, keep branding consistent (colours, fonts), use strong portfolio images (as Vector and Beyond does) to build a professional look.

If you like, I can compare cost, templates, pros & cons of Wix vs Shopify specifically for India (Haryana/Delhi region pricing, payment gateways, compliance) so you can pick with local context. Would you like me to pull that?

Good question yes, the market for creative/branding agencies in the Delhi NCR region is quite crowded, but that doesnt necessarily mean theres no room. Heres a breakdown of what I found + what it means for you.

What the data shows

  • There are many agencies listed simply under branding or creative categories in Delhi/ Delhi NCR. For instance, a directory shows dozens of branding companies in Delhi. creativeorion.com+3Sortlist+3Clutch+3

  • One agency mentions that with 22+ years of experience theyve helped 8,000+ brands in Delhi NCR. designerpeople.com

  • Creative-agency directories list top 10, top 20 agencies in Delhi in 2025. DesignRush+2prettifycreative.com+2

What saturated means here

  • Competition is high: Because there are many firms offering similar services (branding, logos, identity, digital marketing) you will face stiff competition.

  • Differentiation matters: With many players, agencies that stand out (niche focus, exceptional quality, unique style, strong client results) will do better.

  • Niche or specialization helps: If you just do general branding youll be one of many. But if you specialize (say: branding for education & ed-tech startups, or luxury-brand identity for Indian premium market) you can carve a gap.

  • Pricing & value matters: Because many agencies compete on cost too, youll need to decide if you compete on lower-cost or premium value.

  • New agencies can still succeed: Saturation doesnt preclude success if you pick your angle right, build a strong portfolio, and market yourself well.

What this means for you

  • Since you are starting an agency (as it seems), youll want to choose a clear niche (industry, service type, client size) rather than trying to appeal to everyone.

  • Leverage your unique background or style maybe you have storytelling, design, branding passion, student perspective etc make that part of your brand.

  • Build a strong portfolio, even with small clients, so you can show proof.

  • Be clear about what you wont do: This helps avoid you being another jack-of-all-services with no identity.

  • Marketing your agency will matter: local networking in Delhi NCR, online presence (website, LinkedIn, Instagram) since the space is crowded you must be visible.

  • Pricing strategy: You can consider starting modestly to build reputation then move up.

Quick checklist try these now (in this order)

  1. Repo name is correct

    • Your repo must be <your-username>.github.io exactly.

    • From your screenshots it should be aureliandesignhouse.github.io confirm your GitHub username is aureliandesignhouse.

    • If username differs, rename repo accordingly.

  2. Files are in the repository root (not in a folder)

    • On the repo page you must see index.html and styles.css listed at the top level (not inside any folder).

    • If theyre inside a folder (e.g., aurelian_site/index.html) move them to the root.

  3. Index filename correct

    • File must be named index.html (all lowercase). Index.html or index.HTML can fail.

  4. Repository visibility

    • Repo must be Public. (Private repos need a paid Pages plan for user pages.)

  5. Commit & Branch

    • After uploading you must Commit changes.

    • Pages must be set to use the branch where you committed (usually main).

      • Go to Settings Pages under Build and deployment verify Source: Branch = main / (root) is selected.

  6. Check GitHub Pages status / errors

    • In Settings Pages GitHub shows the published URL or an error message.

    • If theres a DNS/CNAME error or build error it will appear there. Read that message.

  7. Open the direct URL

    • Try: https://aureliandesignhouse.github.io/index.html (this forces the file)

    • If that shows the page but https://aureliandesignhouse.github.io does not, this indicates a redirect or cache issue.

  8. Wait a moment

    • After first commit, Pages can take up to a minute or two. (Usually quick.)

  9. HTTPS / Enforce HTTPS

    • In Settings Pages enable Enforce HTTPS if available. If its pending, wait a few minutes.

  10. Common extra issues

    • If you uploaded a CNAME file by mistake that points to a custom domain and DNS isnt configured, Pages may not publish delete the CNAME file or configure DNS.

    • If your site is blank but loads HTML (view source) confirm index.html isn't empty.

    • If you used README.md as homepage instead of index.html, GitHub will show the repo README not site content.

  2. Click Settings Pages. What does it show under Published site? (It either shows the URL or an error/warning).
